      <h1>BMI Chart for Adults: What Your Number Means</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Body Mass Index (BMI) is one of the most widely used health screening tools in the world. Doctors, health organizations, and insurance companies rely on it as a quick, inexpensive way to categorize body weight relative to height. Your BMI can indicate whether you are underweight, normal weight, overweight, or obese — and each category carries different health implications. This guide provides a comprehensive BMI chart organized by height and weight, explains how BMI is calculated, details the health risks associated with each category, discusses the significant limitations of BMI as a health metric, and offers guidance on when a BMI reading should prompt a conversation with your doctor.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>How BMI Is Calculated</h2>
    <p>BMI is calculated by dividing a person's weight by the square of their height. There are two versions of the formula depending on which unit system you use:</p>

    <h3>Metric Formula</h3>
    <p><strong>BMI = weight (kg) / height (m)&sup2;</strong></p>
    <p>Example: A person weighing 70 kg who is 1.75 m tall has a BMI of 70 / (1.75 &times; 1.75) = 70 / 3.0625 = 22.9.</p>

    <h3>Imperial Formula</h3>
    <p><strong>BMI = (weight (lbs) &times; 703) / height (inches)&sup2;</strong></p>
    <p>Example: A person weighing 155 lbs who is 5'9" (69 inches) has a BMI of (155 &times; 703) / (69 &times; 69) = 108,965 / 4,761 = 22.9.</p>
    <p>Both formulas produce the same result. The factor of 703 in the imperial formula is simply a conversion constant that accounts for the difference between metric and imperial units. For instant calculations, use our <a href="/bmi/">BMI calculator</a>.</p>

    <h2>BMI Categories and Health Risks</h2>
    <p>The World Health Organization (WHO) defines four primary BMI categories for adults. Understanding what each category means — and the health risks associated with it — is essential for interpreting your BMI correctly.</p>
