    <h3>Underweight (BMI Below 18.5)</h3>
    <p>Being underweight carries its own set of health risks that are often overlooked in a culture focused on weight loss. Underweight individuals face increased risk of nutritional deficiencies (particularly iron, vitamin D, and calcium), weakened immune function leading to more frequent infections, osteoporosis and increased fracture risk, fertility problems in women (irregular or absent periods), and complications during surgery or illness due to lack of body reserves. Causes of being underweight include genetic factors, eating disorders, hyperthyroidism, celiac disease, chronic infections, and certain medications. If your BMI consistently falls below 18.5, a medical evaluation is warranted.</p>

    <h3>Normal Weight (BMI 18.5 to 24.9)</h3>
    <p>A BMI in the normal range is associated with the lowest overall risk of weight-related health conditions. People in this range generally have healthier blood pressure, blood sugar, and cholesterol levels. However, a normal BMI does not guarantee good health — someone can have a normal BMI while being physically unfit, having a poor diet, or carrying excess visceral fat around their organs. Lifestyle factors like physical activity, diet quality, sleep, and stress management matter as much as the number on the scale.</p>

    <h3>Overweight (BMI 25.0 to 29.9)</h3>
    <p>The overweight category encompasses a wide range of body compositions. Some people in this range are genuinely carrying excess body fat that increases their health risk, while others — particularly those who exercise regularly — may have a higher BMI due to muscle mass. Research indicates that moderately overweight individuals who are physically active and metabolically healthy may not face significantly elevated health risks compared to normal-weight individuals. However, a BMI in this range combined with a sedentary lifestyle, large waist circumference, elevated blood pressure, or high blood sugar does warrant attention. Use our <a href="/body-fat-calculator/">body fat calculator</a> to get a more nuanced picture of your body composition.</p>

    <h3>Obese (BMI 30.0 and Above)</h3>
    <p>Obesity is associated with a significantly increased risk of numerous serious health conditions. The risk increases progressively through the three obesity classes. Key health risks include type 2 diabetes (risk is 7 to 12 times higher compared to normal weight), heart disease and stroke, high blood pressure, several types of cancer (including colorectal, breast, endometrial, and kidney), sleep apnea and breathing difficulties, osteoarthritis from excess joint stress, gallbladder disease, fatty liver disease, and mental health effects including depression and reduced quality of life. It is important to note that weight loss of even 5 to 10 percent of body weight can produce meaningful improvements in many of these risk factors.</p>

