    <h2>Limitations of BMI: What It Cannot Tell You</h2>
    <p>While BMI is a useful screening tool, it has significant limitations that are important to understand. Relying solely on BMI for health decisions can be misleading.</p>

    <h3>Muscle Mass</h3>
    <p>BMI cannot distinguish between muscle and fat. Since muscle is denser than fat, a muscular person weighs more than a non-muscular person of the same height and body fat level. This means that athletes, bodybuilders, and anyone who engages in significant strength training may have a BMI in the overweight or even obese range while having a perfectly healthy body fat percentage. For example, many NFL players have BMIs above 30, and even lean athletes like basketball players often register as "overweight" by BMI standards.</p>

    <h3>Age</h3>
    <p>The standard BMI categories were developed primarily for adults aged 20 to 65. As people age, they tend to lose muscle mass (a process called sarcopenia) and gain fat mass, even if their weight stays the same. This means an older adult with a "normal" BMI may actually have an unhealthily high body fat percentage. Conversely, research suggests that being slightly overweight (BMI 25 to 27) in older age may offer a survival advantage, possibly because extra reserves help during illness or surgery.</p>

    <h3>Ethnicity and Body Composition</h3>
    <p>BMI does not account for ethnic differences in body composition and fat distribution. Research has shown that at the same BMI, Asian populations tend to have higher body fat percentages and a greater risk of type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease compared to White populations. This has led the WHO to propose lower BMI cutoffs for Asian populations — with overweight starting at 23 rather than 25, and obesity starting at 27.5 rather than 30. Conversely, some studies suggest that certain Pacific Islander and Black populations may have lower body fat percentages at the same BMI compared to White populations.</p>

    <h3>Fat Distribution</h3>
    <p>Where you carry your fat matters as much as how much fat you carry, and BMI tells you nothing about fat distribution. Visceral fat (fat stored around your internal organs in the abdominal area) is far more metabolically dangerous than subcutaneous fat (fat stored under the skin). Two people with identical BMIs can have very different health risk profiles depending on their fat distribution — someone with most of their fat around their midsection faces higher risks than someone whose fat is more evenly distributed.</p>

    <h3>Gender</h3>
    <p>Women naturally have a higher body fat percentage than men at any given BMI. A healthy body fat percentage for women is approximately 21 to 33 percent, while for men it is 8 to 21 percent. Despite this significant difference in body composition, the standard BMI categories use the same cutoffs for both sexes. This means BMI may slightly overestimate health risk for muscular men and slightly underestimate it for women with high body fat but average weight.</p>

    <h2>Waist Circumference: A Key Supplement to BMI</h2>
    <p>Because BMI cannot measure fat distribution, health professionals often use waist circumference as a complementary measurement. Waist circumference is a better indicator of visceral (abdominal) fat, which is more closely linked to metabolic disease than total body fat.</p>
